default2. Do authorities take sufficient advantage of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities, including those available from central government? In addition, the Committee would welcome information on PFI contracts and their operation with local government.default&#xa0;
defaultLocal Government does not take advantage enough of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities. Our perception of the barriers to this are; different rules in each organisation; the timings of contract end dates and the lack of motivation for one or more partner to extend their contract in order to align timings; lack of regional leadership and coordination; no mandate to drive collaboration jus
defaultt enthusiasm of the willing few
default;
default and the perceived
default threat of a ‘shared service’ if we procure together.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe solution could be; aligning rules and p
defaultrocesses; developing a partnership 
defaultapproach to contract management i.e. one contract register which could be facilitated 
defaultthrough an e-solution and sharing
default spend data in order that we have joint planning and i
defaultdentify aggregate opportunities. All of this
default requires strong commitment and clear 
defaultcross-partner
default leadership to allow all of these opportunities to be explored and then implemented. We should approach procurement as ‘one buyer’.
default This doesn’t have to be a regional approach just a collaborative approach where more than one public sector partner works together.
default&#xa0;
defaultCentral government opportunities as well as other 
defaultcentral purchasing bodies
default are mostly explored as part of our pre-procurement activi
defaultty in Halton to ensure we bench
defaultmark in order to seek the best route to market.
defaultIn Halton we do have a PFI contract as part of BSF. We have an established LEP which is considered as part of the pre procurement process for 
defaultconstruction spend and is bench
defaultmarked accordingly as this is a pre-procured route so can offer some value for money.
default This is a Joint Venture Company where Halton BC is a 10% shareholder.
