default4. To what extent is risk in local government procurement and contracting understood and managed and contracting strategies adopted, which are tailored to product and supplier market places? More specifically, do local authorities maintain and operate effective client management functions and have they entered contractual arrangements which allow the flexibility to meet changing circumstances such as budget reductions or changes in the way a service has to be delivered?default&#xa0;
defaultHalton underpins all procurement 
defaultactivity with a
default risk assessment 
defaultprocess (Risk Based Sourcing - RBS) for all spend below EU financial thresholds and this replaces the PQQ. 
defaultUnderstanding of risk is paramount and this sits at the start
default of the pre-procurement process as we focus on risk not value below EU.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs part of this pre-procurement risk assessment 
defaultprocess 
defaultofficers explore risk in e
defaultvery respect in order that 
defaultrisk
defaults are
default identified 
defaultand then
default 
defaultremoved, reduced or managed 
defaultthroughout
default the procurement process and
default the life of the 
defaultcontract.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe do operate an effective client management function as we manage our procurement on a category basis and this links to contract management which sits with the client department but we maintain a commercial contract management function centrally and contract register.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe do build in at the pre-procurement stage as part of the risk assessment process a step to secure funding availability and approval in order to identify any risk; we work closely with our finance department. This allows us to build in to both the procurement process and contract management process lean procurement principles in order to respond to change.
